# Rate Limits

The Payments Domain enforces rate limits to ensure system stability.

## Global Limits

* 1000 requests per second per client (default)
* Burst allowance up to 2000 requests

---

## Per-Endpoint Limits

| Endpoint       | Limit        |
| -------------- | ------------ |
| POST /payments | 200 req/sec  |
| GET /payments  | 500 req/sec  |
| POST /refunds  | 100 req/sec  |
| GET /status    | 1000 req/sec |

---

## Rate Limit Headers

All responses include:

```
X-RateLimit-Limit
X-RateLimit-Remaining
X-RateLimit-Reset
```

---

## Behavior on Exceeding Limits

* Returns `429 Too Many Requests`
* Includes retry-after header
* Requests must be retried using exponential backoff

---

## Best Practices

* Implement client-side throttling
* Use batching where possible
* Avoid aggressive polling of payment status
* Prefer event-driven updates over repeated GET calls

---

# Summary

Integration with the Payments Domain requires careful handling of:

* Secure authentication
* Strict idempotency rules
* Controlled retry behavior
* Structured failure handling
* Respect for rate limits

Systems that follow these guidelines will achieve reliable, predictable integration with minimal operational issues.
